The Reality

574 nations. 56 million acres.
540,000 unserved homes.

Grandma can't get on a telehealth call, so she drives three hours to IHS and waits six more. This isn't a "digital divide" statistic on somebody's grant proposal. This is daily life.

WORLD MOBILE
The Real Reason
Why It Persists

They did the math and kept driving.

AT&T, Verizon, T-Mobile — they build where the money is. Low population density, tough terrain, trust land they don't want to navigate? They wrote it off.

The FCC throws billions at "rural broadband" and somehow the money never makes it past the county line. Indian Country got skipped, not by accident, but by business model.

World Mobile is a different model. We don't need a million subscribers per tower to make it work. We need a community that's ready to own its own network.

The Traditional Telco Model

  • Build expensive towers → charge monthly fees
  • Profit must justify per-mile infrastructure cost
  • Low-density areas = low ROI = ignored
  • Revenue leaves the community entirely
  • Tribal sovereignty = regulatory complexity they avoid

The World Mobile Model

  • Community hosts nodes → community earns
  • Sharing economy: low cost, high reach
  • Works WITH tribal sovereignty, not around it
  • Revenue stays in the nation
  • Tribal spectrum, tribal network, tribal future

WORLD MOBILE
Portal AirNode
The Hardware

Portal AirNode

The Portal is your community's wireless access point. Compact, easy to install, and designed for the sharing economy. A community member hosts it — on a home, a community building, a tribal office — and it provides Wi-Fi coverage to the surrounding area.

  • Plug-and-play setup — no telecom degree required
  • Wi-Fi coverage radius of approximately 150 meters
  • Connects to the World Mobile network via backhaul
  • Host earns WMTx token rewards for network usage
  • Validated and authenticated on the World Mobile blockchain
  • Operates on CBRS and licensed spectrum bands

Network Role
The Backbone

Titan AirNode

The Titan is the heavy lifter. Deployed on towers, elevated structures, or existing tribal infrastructure, it provides extended-range, high-capacity coverage — the anchor that ties your network together.

  • Extended coverage area for wide community reach
  • High-throughput backbone for dense usage areas
  • Mounts on existing towers, buildings, or water tanks
  • Supports licensed spectrum including tribal 2.5 GHz
  • Connects multiple Portals to form a mesh network
  • Tribal-operated and maintained — local jobs, local control

Together, Portals and Titans create a complete community network — Titans provide the backbone and reach, Portals fill in neighborhood-level coverage. All community-owned.

WORLD MOBILE
Tribal Spectrum
Sovereignty in the Airwaves

Your spectrum is sitting there.
Let's activate it.

A lot of tribes are sitting on 2.5 GHz spectrum rights. The FCC recognized tribal priority for this band, and many nations hold licenses. But right now? That spectrum is doing nothing. It's like having oil under your land and no drill.

World Mobile brings the infrastructure — the Portals, the Titan AirNodes, the backhaul — to light that spectrum up. The tribe keeps ownership. The tribe operates the network. WM provides the technology and the know-how to get it live.

Your spectrum, activated by your people, serving your community. That's how it should've been from the start.

World Mobile Spectrum

Licensed spectrum in CA, NM, NV, UT. CBRS nationwide. Hybrid network combining tribal 2.5 GHz + WM spectrum + CBRS for complete coverage.

Instead of paying Verizon, your bill stays home.

Cycle Repeats

Host a Node

Provide a location (rooftop, tower, building). The node does the rest. You earn WMTx rewards 24/7 based on network usage through your node.

Tribal Revenue

Unlike traditional telcos where every dollar leaves, the sharing economy keeps a share of revenue circulating within the nation. The more the network grows, the more the community earns.

WMTx Token

Listed on Coinbase. Core staking yields up to ~5% APY (variable, not guaranteed). Operators earn through the fiat-to-token flywheel — real subscriber revenue backing real rewards.

Deploy and mount Portal and Titan AirNodes. Skilled technical work with hands-on training. Your nephew who's good with his hands? Career path.

Hosts

WORLD MOBILE
Culture & Connectivity
Strengthening, Not Replacing

Connectivity carries culture further
than the rez road ever could.

Some people hear "internet" and think it's all TikTok and distractions. Here's what connectivity actually looks like in Indian Country:

🎤 Language Preservation

Elders record lessons that reach every classroom in the nation. Language apps built by tribal members, for tribal members. Immersion programs that connect across distance.

👩‍⚕️ Telehealth Access

No more 3-hour drives to IHS. Virtual consultations from home. Mental health services that reach every corner of the reservation. Elder care without the burden of travel.

📚 Education Equity

Kids do homework at home, not in a parking lot. Online courses. Virtual tutoring. Tribal colleges reaching students who can't relocate. Equal access to what every other kid in America has.

📰 Tribal Media

Your own news. Your own stories. Told by your own people, reaching everyone. Not filtered through outside outlets that get it wrong. Sovereign storytelling on sovereign networks.

🏘️ Urban NDN Connection

Urban NDNs staying connected to their nation's council meetings, community events, and family. Grandma doing a video call with grandkids who had to move to the city for work.

💸 Small Business

Rez entrepreneurs can finally take card payments, list on Google, sell online. Artisans reaching customers worldwide. Tourism sites that actually load. Economic self-determination.

Monthly discount
on tribal lands
Free
Smartphone

Tribal Broadband Base Plan: 2,000 minutes + 1,000 texts + 4.5GB data at no charge monthly. Call 888-716-8880 to apply.

FCC Enhanced Tribal Lifeline

The Lifeline program provides $34.25/month toward phone or internet for eligible households on tribal lands (vs. $9.25 standard). Qualifications include Medicaid, SNAP, SSI, Federal Public Housing, Veterans Pension, BIA assistance, Tribal TANF, FDPIR, or Tribal Head Start.

Federal Broadband Funding for Tribes

Program Funding Key Detail
NTIA Tribal Broadband
Connectivity Program		 $3 billion 275 awards to date. ~$500M+ remaining for Spring 2026 NOFO
USDA ReConnect $150M tribal set-aside 100% grants, no matching funds required for tribes

World Mobile's team assists tribal partners in identifying and applying for applicable federal programs. Combined with the sharing economy model, this creates a pathway to affordable, sustainable connectivity.

Proof Points
It's Already Working

Tribal broadband is proven.
Community ownership works.

Across Indian Country, tribes are already building and owning their networks. World Mobile's decentralized model builds on what's working — with simpler deployment, lower cost, and built-in revenue sharing.

Southern California Tribal Digital Village

19 Tribes. 17 Reservations.

  • 350+ miles of wireless links
  • 86 tribal buildings connected
  • Free internet to schools, libraries, and health centers
  • 2016 CENIC Innovation Award

Proof that tribal-owned wireless networks serve communities better than any outside provider.

Navajo Tribal Utility Authority

15,000 sq mi. Tribal-owned.

  • 59 wireless towers deployed
  • 550 miles of fiber backbone
  • $32M federal grant secured
  • One of largest tribal-owned utilities in the US

When tribes control their infrastructure, coverage happens — even across the most challenging terrain.

World Mobile: Oregon & Beyond

Sharing economy. Live in the US.

  • Partnership with Adaptive Broadband (Oregon)
  • 70+ radios/towers converted to AirNodes
  • Licensed spectrum in CA, NM, NV, UT
  • 52nd licensed MNO in the USA

World Mobile is already live and operational. The next step: Indian Country.

Let's Build This
Next Steps

Stoodis.

We didn't come here to sell you something. We came because this technology works, tribal nations deserve to own it, and nobody else is bringing it to the table on these terms.

No long-term extraction contracts. No "we'll build it and you'll rent it" hustle. The network belongs to the community. The revenue belongs to the community. The jobs belong to the community.

1. Tribal Council Meeting

We sit down with your leadership. Understand your community's needs, existing infrastructure, and spectrum holdings. No pitch decks — just conversation.

2. Coverage Assessment

Our team surveys the land. Maps optimal Titan and Portal placement. Identifies backhaul options and federal funding paths that match your situation.

3. Community Deployment

Train tribal members. Install the hardware. Light up the network. From first conversation to live coverage — your people build it, your people own it.
